Cardiovascular diseases and respiratory impairments in patients lead to difficulties in breathing and negative effects on their overall well-being. Clinical sleep analysis, a vital tool for early diagnosis and treatment, traditionally relies on expensive polysomnography systems. Recent advances in audio signal processing and machine learning have opened the door to more accessible and cost-effective alternatives. This paper introduces a novel spectro-temporal convolutional network to estimate critical sleep parameters from audio recordings captured by a single microphone. Empirical evaluations on a public dataset of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease patients indicate that the proposed framework surpasses current state-of-the-art approaches and shows significant improvements in predicting sleep quality metrics (including sleep duration, sleep fragmentation index, and apnea-hypopnea index), while utilizing fewer parameters and alleviating the need for manual feature extraction.

Neurological disorders and cognitive impairments in individuals lead to difficulties in communication and negative effects on their daily functioning. Clinical language analysis, a vital tool for early diagnosis and treatment, traditionally relies on expensive speech recognition systems. Recent advances in audio signal processing and machine learning have opened the door to more accessible and cost-effective alternatives. This paper introduces a novel recurrent neural network to estimate critical language parameters from audio recordings captured by a single microphone. Empirical evaluations on a public dataset of individuals with autism spectrum disorder indicate that the proposed framework surpasses current state-of-the-art approaches and shows significant improvements in predicting language processing metrics (including language comprehension, language production, and social communication skills), while utilizing fewer parameters and alleviating the need for manual feature extraction.

Cardiovascular diseases and physical limitations in individuals lead to difficulties in mobility and negative effects on their daily functioning. Clinical gait analysis, a vital tool for early diagnosis and treatment, traditionally relies on expensive motion capture systems. Recent advances in sensor signal processing and machine learning have opened the door to more accessible and cost-effective alternatives. This paper introduces a novel convolutional neural network to estimate critical gait parameters from sensor recordings captured by a single wearable device. Empirical evaluations on a public dataset of individuals with Parkinson's disease indicate that the proposed framework surpasses current state-of-the-art approaches and shows significant improvements in predicting gait processing metrics (including balance, coordination, and mobility), while utilizing fewer parameters and alleviating the need for manual feature extraction.
